'''Randal Howard''' "'''Rand'''" '''Paul''' (born January 7, 1963) is the [[Seniority in the United States Senate|junior]] [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] for [[Kentucky]]. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. A member of the [[Tea Party movement]], he describes himself as a "constitutional conservative"<ref>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Deborah |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/04/magazine/04fob-q4-t.html |title=Questions for Rand Paul <U+2013> Tea Time Interview |publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=October 23, 2010 |date=March 29, 2010}}</ref> and a [[libertarianism|libertarian]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Martina |url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/05/04/im-very-serious-about-running-ron-pauls-son-says/ |title='I'm very serious about running,' Ron Paul's son says |publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 15, 2010 |date=May 4, 2010}}</ref> He is the son of former Congressman  [[Ron Paul]] of [[Texas|Texas,]] who ran for [[President of the United States|president]] in [[Ron Paul presidential campaign, 1988|1988]] as a libertarian, and in [[Ron Paul presidential campaign, 2008|2008]] and [[Ron Paul presidential campaign, 2012|2012]] as a Republican. He first received national attention in 2008 when making political speeches on behalf of his father and is the first United States Senator to serve simultaneously with a parent in the [[United States House of Representatives]].

A graduate of the [[Duke University School of Medicine]], Paul has been a practicing [[ophthalmologist]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky|Bowling Green]], [[Kentucky]], since 1993, and established his own clinic in December 2007. In 1994, he founded Kentucky Taxpayers United, of which he is still the chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/10/14/rand-pauls-antitax-group-has-been-inactive-for-years/ |title="Rand Paul<U+2019>s Antitax Group Has Been Inactive for Years" (October 15, 2010) Wall Street Journal |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=October 14, 2010 |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref>

In 2010, Paul ran as the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for the United States Senate seat being vacated by retiring Senator [[Jim Bunning]] of Kentucky, beating [[Secretary of State of Kentucky|Kentucky Secretary of State]] [[Trey Grayson]] in the primary. Despite the fact that he had never previously held political office, he defeated [[Attorney General of Kentucky|Kentucky Attorney General]] [[Jack Conway (politician)|Jack Conway]]. As a supporter of the Tea Party movement, he has been vocal in advocating for [[term limit]]s, a [[Balanced Budget Amendment#United States|balanced budget amendment]], and the [[Read the Bills Act]], in addition to the widespread reduction of federal spending and taxation. He has gained prominence for his independent positions on many political issues, often clashing with both Republicans and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].<ref name="schreiner1">{{cite web |url=http://dailycaller.com/2010/09/12/paul-says-gop-shares-blame-for-deficits/ |title=Paul says GOP shares blame for deficits |publisher=The Daily Caller |accessdate=October 23, 2010 |date=September 12, 2010 |last=Schreiner |first=Bruce}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Randal Howard Paul<ref>{{cite web|last=Alessi|first=Ryan|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2010/04/20/1231313/pauls-small-government-message.html#more|title=Paul's top goal is to cut federal spending|publisher = ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]''|accessdate=December 16, 2010|date=September 13, 2010}}</ref> was born on January 7, 1963, in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], to Carol (Wells) Paul and [[Ron Paul]]. His father is a physician and former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] of [[Texas's 14th congressional district]]. The [[Birth order|middle child]] of five, his siblings are Ronald "Ronnie" Paul Jr., Lori Paul Pyeatt, Robert Paul and Joy Paul-LeBlanc.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stonington|first=Joel|url=http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/10/04/how-old-is-rand-paul/|title=How Old Is Rand Paul?|publisher=[[Politics Daily]]|accessdate=December 16, 2010|date=October 4, 2010}}</ref> Paul was [[baptism|baptized]] in the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]]<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Bryan|first=Jason|url=http://www.politicsdaily.com/2010/10/25/what-is-rand-pauls-religion/|title=What Is Rand Paul's Religion?|publisher=Politics Daily|accessdate=January 31, 2011|date=October 25, 2010}}</ref> and identified as a practicing [[Christian]] as a teenager.<ref name="AW">{{cite news|last =Wolfson|first =Andrew|title =Rand Paul rides tide of anti-Washington sentiment|publisher =''[[The Courier-Journal]]''|date =October 18, 2010|url =http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/2166776301.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+18%2C+2010&author=Andrew+Wolfson&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=n%2Fa&desc=Rand+Paul+rides+tide+of+anti-Washington+sentiment|accessdate =February 23, 2011}}</ref> Despite his father's [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] views and strong support for [[Individual and group rights|individual rights]],<ref name="AW"/><ref>{{cite web|last =Healy|first =Gene| authorlink =Gene Healy|title =Rand Paul, Anti-Incumbent Republican|publisher =[[Cato Institute]]|date =May 18, 2010|url =http://www.cato.org/pub_display.php?pub_id=11819|accessdate =February 8, 2011|quote =Given father Ron's libertarian convictions, people often assume that he is named after the self-styled 'radical for capitalism' who wrote ''[[Atlas Shrugged]]''.}}</ref> the novelist [[Ayn Rand]] was not the inspiration for his first name; he went by "Randy" while growing up.<ref name="NYT1">{{cite news |last=Leibovich|first=Mark|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/06/us/politics/06paul.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all|title=For Paul Family, Libertarian Ethos Began at Home|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=June 6, 2010|date=June 6, 2010}}</ref> His wife shortened his name to "Rand".<ref name="AW"/><ref name="JR">{{cite web|last=Rettig|first=Jessica|url=http://politics.usnews.com/news/articles/2010/06/03/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-rand-paul.html|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Rand Paul |publisher =''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''|accessdate=December 12, 2010|date=June 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Burnette|first=Eric|url=http://www.louisville.com/content/gospel-according-paul-louisville-magazines-inside-look-us-senate-candidate-rand-paul-news|title=The Gospel According to Paul: Louisville Magazine's inside look at U.S. Senate candidate Rand Paul|publisher =''[[Louisville Magazine]]''|accessdate=December 30, 2010|date=September 7, 2010}}</ref>

The Paul family moved to [[Lake Jackson, Texas]], in 1968,<ref name="NYT1"/><ref name="WM"/> where Rand was raised<ref name="JH">{{cite news|last=Horowitz|first=Jason|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/03/AR2010020303643.html|title=Running for Senate, Rand Paul lights a fire under Kentucky GOP|publisher =''[[The Washington Post]]''|accessdate=February 23, 2011|date=February 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wolfford|first=David|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/229456/rand-against-machine/david-wolfford|title=Rand against the Machine|publisher =''[[National Review]]''|accessdate=February 23, 2011|date=April 5, 2010}}</ref> and his father began his medical practice and for an extent of time was the only [[Obstetrics|obstetrician]] in [[Brazoria County, Texas|Brazoria County]].<ref name="NYT1"/><ref name="WM">{{Cite book|last=Watterson|first=Mark|title =Don't Weep for Me, America: How Democracy in America Became the Prince (While We Slept)| publisher=Dorrance Publishing|year=2008|page=203|isbn=978-0-8059-7890-2 }}
* {{cite news|last=Sherman|first=Jerome L.|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07215/806597-176.stm|title=Texas congressman brings presidential campaign to hometown|publisher =''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''|accessdate=February 12, 2011|date=August 3, 2007|quote=He and his wife decided to settle in the southeastern Texan town of Lake Jackson, near the site of his military service. For a period, Paul was the only obstetrician in Brazoria County, and he delivered as many as 50 babies a month.}}</ref> When he was 13, his father was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Straub|first=Bill|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/2010/sep/19/rand-paul/|title=Off and running: Rand Paul|publisher =''[[Evansville Courier & Press]]''|accessdate=February 23, 2011|date=September 19, 2010}}</ref> In his teenage years, Paul studied the [[Austrian School|Austrian economists]] that his father respected, as well as Ayn Rand.<ref name="NYT1"/> Paul went to [[Brazoswood High School]] and was on the swimming team and played defensive back on the football team.<ref name="AW"/><ref name="JH"/> Paul attended [[Baylor University]] from fall 1981&nbsp;to summer 1984. He was enrolled in the honors program at Baylor, and had scored approximately in the 90th percentile on the [[Medical College Admission Test]].<ref name="Degree">{{cite web|last=Brammer|first=Jack|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2010/08/05/1377392/contrary-to-some-media-reports.html|title=Contrary to some media reports, Rand Paul has no bachelor's degree|publisher=''Lexington Herald-Leader''|date=August 5, 2010|accessdate=September 10, 2010}}</ref> During the time he spent at Baylor, he was involved in the swim team and [[Young Conservatives of Texas]] and was a member of a secret organization known as the [[NoZe Brotherhood]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Brammer|first=Jack|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2010/08/11/1385157/paul-calls-allegations-in-gq-story.html|title=Paul: GQ allegations 'absolutely untrue'|publisher = ''Lexington Herald-Leader''|accessdate=February 27, 2011|date=September 28, 2010}}</ref> Paul left Baylor early when he was accepted into the [[Duke University School of Medicine]], where he earned his [[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.) degree in 1988&nbsp;and completed his [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in othalmology, also at Duke, in 1993.
==Medical career==

Paul has held a state-issued medical license since moving to Bowling Green in 1993.<ref name="lcj-2010">{{Cite web|last=Gerth|first=Joseph|title=Rand Paul's ophthalmology certification not recognized by national clearinghouse|publisher=''The Courier-Journal''|date=2010-06-14|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/2059232451.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+14%2C+2010&author=Joseph+Gerth&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=n%2Fa&desc=Rand+Paul%27s+ophthalmology+certification+not+recognized+by+national+clearinghouse|accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref> He received his first job from Dr. John Downing of Downing McPeak Vision Centers, which brought him to Bowling Green after completing his residency. Paul worked for Downing for about five years before parting ways. Afterwards, he went to work at the Gilbert Graves Clinic, a private medical group in Bowling Green, for 10&nbsp;years before creating his own practice in a converted one-story house across the street from Downing's office.<ref name="AVB"/> After his election to the U.S. Senate, he merged his practice with Downing's medical practice.<ref>{{Cite web|last =Harmon|first =Hayley|title =Rand Paul's Practice Merges with Downing-McPeak|publisher =[[WBKO]]|date =2011-01-05|url =http://www.wbko.com/home/headlines/Rand_Pauls_Practice_Merges_with_Downing-McPeak_112968089.html|accessdate =2011-03-12}}</ref> Paul has had two malpractice lawsuits filed against him since 1993;  was cleared in one case and the other was settled for $50,000.<ref name="AVB">{{Cite web|last =Van Benschoten|first =Amanda|title =Rand Paul's political rise surprises even those in Bowling Green|publisher =''The Courier-Journal''|date =2010-07-05|url =http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20100705/NEWS0106/7050340/Rand-Paul-s-political-rise-surprises-even-those-Bowling-Green|accessdate =2011-03-06}}</ref> Regardless, his medical work has been praised by Downing and he has medical privileges at two Bowling Green hospitals.<ref name="lcj-2010"/><ref name="AVB"/> Paul specializes in cataract and glaucoma surgeries, LASIK procedures, and corneal transplants.<ref name="JR"/>

In 1995, Paul passed the [[American Board of Ophthalmology]] (ABO) boards on his first attempt and earned board-certification under the ABO for a decade. In 1997, to protest the ABO's decision to [[grandfather clause|grandfather]] in older ophthalmologists and not require them to recertify, Paul, along with 200&nbsp;ophthalmologists formed the National Board of Ophthalmology (NBO).<ref>{{cite web|last=Weigel|first=David|title=Rand Paul: I passed my ophthalmology certification, but took a stand against the way the board operates|publisher=''The Washington Post''|date=2010-06-14|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/06/rand_paul_i_passed_my_opthamal.html|accessdate=2011-03-22}}</ref> Paul's ophthalmology board is not officially recognized by the [[American Board of Medical Specialties]] (ABMS). The NBO was incorporated in 1999, but he allowed it to be dissolved in 2000&nbsp;after not filing the required paperwork with the [[Secretary of State of Kentucky|Kentucky Secretary of State]]'s office. Paul later recreated the board in September 2005, three months before his certification from the ABO was scheduled to expire. His ABO certification lapsed on December 31, 2005. Paul has since been certified by the NBO.<ref name="lcj-2010"/>

As a member of the Bowling Green Noon [[Lions Club]], Paul founded the Southern Kentucky Lions Eye Clinic to help provide eye surgery and exams for those who cannot afford to pay.<ref name=mt/> He is a regular presenter at the annual Men's Health and Safety Day conference held by [[list of hospitals in Kentucky|The Medical Center of Bowling Green]] since 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BGDB&p_theme=bgdb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10AC7BA223644590&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|date=2002-05-29|accessdate=2009-04-04|publisher=Bowling Green Daily News|title=Men focus of fair <U+2013> Men's Health and Safety Day is designed to help men help themselves}}</ref>

==Political activism==
As founder and chairman of the anti-tax organization Kentucky Taxpayers United (KTU) since 1994, Paul regularly presents "taxpayers' friend" awards to state legislators. KTU, which regards itself as [[nonpartisan]], but is criticized for being ideologically [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]],<ref name=lhl1>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&s_site=kentucky&p_multi=LH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7405EA721DDBE&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work = Lexington Herald-Leader|title=56 Honored by Taxpayers Group|page=C4|date=April 16, 1996|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=lhl2>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&s_site=kentucky&p_multi=LH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7350C1BCFAFDF&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work = Lexington Herald-Leader|title=Legislators Honored as Anti-Tax 'Heroes' But Several Honorees Recently Voted for Tax|page=A12|date=April 13, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> examines legislator records on taxation and spending to inform voters where their own lawmakers stand on the issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-72916086.html|title=8 Legislators Named Friends of Taxpayers|quote=Recognized by Kentucky Taxpayers United were Sens. Gex 'Jay' Williams and Dick Roeding and Reps. Charlie Walton, Paul Marcotte, Katie Stine, Tom Kerr, Dick Murgatroyd and Jon David Reinhardt {{interp|...}} Rand Paul, the group's chairman, said the organization did the ranking so voters could see where their lawmakers stand on the issues.|author=Collins, Michael|work=[[Kentucky Post]]|location=[[Covington, Kentucky]]|date=April 16, 1996|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> Paul's editorial commentary on behalf of KTU has been published and recognized in the ''[[Kentucky Post]]''.<ref name=ky3b/>

KTU sponsors the Taxpayer's Pledge of [[Americans for Tax Reform]], encouraging politicians to pledge publicly to vote uniformly against tax raises.<ref name=ky3b>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63443974.html|title=Not One Cent More|date=March 29, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009|work=Kentucky Post|last=Paul |first=Rand}}</ref> Nine of fifteen Northern Kentucky legislators signed the pledge,<ref name=oh>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63432685.html|title=Pledge May Kill Hotel Tax|date=January 21, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009|work=Cincinnati Post|last=Collins |first=Michael|quote=Any legislator who breaks the pledge can expect to incur the wrath of Paul's group.}}</ref> such as Senator Dick Roeding<ref name=ky3b/> and Representative Royce Adams in 1996.<ref name=ky2>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63435654.html|title=No-Tax Pledges May Fall Adams: Promise Covered First Term|date=February 7, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009|work=Kentucky Post|quote='I have no qualms at calling for the removal of any legislator who would break his pledge,' Paul said. 'We would expend every amount of energy on that person in their next legislative race. This is someone's word of honor. If they break the pledge, I say shame on them, and they should suffer the repercussions.'}}</ref> In 2000, these legislators considered a hotel room tax hike (favored by Governor [[Paul E. Patton|Paul Patton]] for helping expand the Dr. [[Albert B. Sabin]] Convention Center in nearby [[Cincinnati]]), even though the increase might "incur the wrath of Paul's group," as two newspapers put it.<ref name=oh/><ref name=ky1>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63433616.html|title=No-Tax Pledge Binds Lawmakers|date=January 21, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009|work=[[Kentucky Post]]|location=[[Covington, Kentucky]]|quote=Raising the hotel surcharge by 1 cent would amount to a small increase in an existing tax that is really just a user fee. It would not constitute a new tax, they argue. But Kentucky Taxpayers United, the statewide group behind the no-new-taxes pledge, scoffs at that logic. 'Any raise in the tax will break a pledge,' said Rand Paul, a Bowling Green eye doctor who is chairman of the anti-tax group.}}</ref>

Paul stated that Patton's argument for "revenue recovery" was merely a [[euphemism]] for taxes<ref name=ky3a>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-63441148.html|title='Revenue Recovery' or 'User Fee' Sure Sound Like Taxes|date=March 23, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009|work=[[Kentucky Post]]|location=[[Covington, Kentucky]]|quote=Rand Paul, chairman of Kentucky Taxpayers United, said it is a tax increase, pure and simple. 'Nobody seems to be paying much attention to their pledge.'}}</ref> and said that KTU would fight reelection of any pledge-breakers; Adams requested in writing that Paul's group release him from his pledge, stating that it only applied to his first term.<ref name=ky2/> By the close of session in April, the tax increase had failed, although Patton had achieved most of his intended budget; Paul stated legislators were pressured to finalize the budget by deadline rather than to "face accusations of shutting down government."<ref name=ky4>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&s_site=kentucky&p_multi=LH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11F949E1D4051B58&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Session Spins to a Close in Frankfort|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=April 16, 2000|accessdate=April 4, 2009|page=A1|quote=They knew they would face accusations of shutting down government, much as congressional Republicans did five years ago, said Rand Paul.}}</ref>

Paul often speaks on his father's behalf,<ref name=mp>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypaul.com/node/185|title=The First Family???|author=Pyeatt, Matt|date=May 24, 2007|publisher=Daily Paul|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ronpaul2008.com/events/rand-paul/|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080123211511/http://www.ronpaul2008.com/events/rand-paul/|archivedate=January 23, 2008|title=Dr. Rand Paul: Upcoming Events|publisher=[[Ron Paul 2008]]|accessdate=December 20, 2007}}</ref> and he and his son William attended the third Republican presidential debate of 2007 in [[New Hampshire]], as well as campaigned door-to-door in the state for his father.<ref name=bgdn>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bgdailynews.com/articles/2007/06/06/news/news9.txt|work=[[Bowling Green Daily News]]|author=Gaines, Jim|title=Bowling Green ophthalmologist says father, Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, stands a good chance in N.H. primary election|date=June 6, 2007|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref> At a New Hampshire rally with 250 in attendance (plus 30 members of his own family), Paul repeated a campaign [[meme]] by pretending to take a call from [[Rudy Giuliani]] during his remarks, and joking that Giuliani needed campaigners and wanted to borrow the Paul family.<ref name=bg>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/politics/primarysource/2007/09/paul_shows_that.html|author=Pindell, James W.|work=Primary Source|publisher=Boston Globe|title=Paul shows that Romney is not the only one with a big family|date=September 29, 2007|accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>

On December 16, 2007, the 234th anniversary of the [[Boston Tea Party]], Paul spoke at [[Faneuil Hall]] in favor of small government principles,<ref name=nyx>{{Cite news|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/12/16/reinventing-the-revolution/?pagemode=print|publisher=New York Times|work=Caucus|date=December 16, 2007|accessdate=April 4, 2009|title=Reinventing the Revolution|author=Santora, Mark}}</ref> calling for what [[CNN]] termed a "modern day revolution."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0712/17/cnr.08.html|title=Wintry Weather Hits U.S.; Saudis Pardon Rape Victim|author=Collins, Heidi; Snow, Mary|date=December 17, 2007|accessdate=April 4, 2009|publisher=CNN|work=Transcripts}}</ref> He continued campaigning across the country for his father in 2008,<ref name=xmas>{{Cite book|title=Happy Holidays from Congressman Ron Paul and Family|author=Paul, Carol and Ron|date=December 2008|authorlink=Ron Paul}}</ref> traveling as far as [[Montana]].<ref name=mt>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kulr8.com/news/state/13944012.html|publisher=[[KULR-TV]]|date=January 21, 2008|accessdate=April 4, 2009|agency=Associated Press|title=Son of long-shot presidential hopeful to visit Montana|location=[[Billings, Montana]]}}</ref>

Paul has co-authored a book entitled ''The Tea Party Goes to Washington'' with Jack Hunter, released on February 22, 2011.<ref>''The Tea Party Goes to Washington'', Nashville: Center Street, 2011. 254 pp.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lowman|first=Stephen|title=Every Congress member to get Rand Paul's book|publisher=''The Washington Post''|date=February 22, 2011|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/political-bookworm/2011/02/every_member_of_congress_is_ge.html|accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref> He also released a second book titled ''Government Bullies: How Everyday Americans Are Being Harassed, Abused, and Imprisoned by the Feds'', which was released on September 12, 2012.<ref>{{ASIN | 1455522759 }}</ref>

==Electoral history==
{{See also|United States Senate election in Kentucky, 2010}}

===Primary campaign===
[[File:Rand Paul in Louisville by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Then-U.S. Senate candidate Rand Paul speaking with a supporter at a healthcare rally in Louisville, Kentucky in November 2009.]]

In the beginning of 2009, Paul was the focus of an online grassroots movement to [[Draft (politics)|draft]] him in a bid to replace beleaguered Republican Kentucky senator [[Jim Bunning]]. The news of his potential candidacy became a topic of national interest and was discussed in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/washington/2009/03/ron-paul-defend.html |title=Ron Paul defends earmarks, says anti-pork McCain is just grandstanding |publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com |date=March 11, 2009 |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> and locally in the Kentucky press.<ref name=ky5>[http://kywordsmith.com/#/rand-paul-issues/4533680792 "Rand Paul Set To Launch"], www.kywordsmith.com. May 9, 2009</ref> Commenting on Paul's possible candidacy, his father noted that "Should Senator Bunning decide not to run, I think Rand would make a great U.S. Senator."<ref>{{cite news|title=Congressman Paul's Statement on His Son Rand Paul|author=Martin, T.|work=Pediatrics Week|date=March 21, 2009}}</ref>

On May 1, 2009, Paul officially confirmed that if Bunning, whose fundraising in 2009 has matched his poor numbers in opinion polling for the 2010 election,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fivethirtyeight.com/2009/05/bunning-retirement-might-not-save-gop.html|title=Bunning Retirement Might Not Save GOP in Kentucky|agency=FiveThirtyEight.com|first=Nate|last=Silver|date=May 1, 2009}}</ref> declined to seek a third term, he would almost certainly run in the [[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]] primary to succeed him,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wbko.com/news/headlines/44184752.html|title=Dr. Rand Paul Ready To Enter Primary For Bunning's Seat|agency=WBKO|date=May 1, 2009}}</ref> and formed an [[exploratory committee]] soon after, while still promising to stay out of the race if Bunning had ultimately decided to run for re-election. Paul made this announcement on [[MSNBC|MSNBC's]] ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', though a local Kentucky news site first broke the news.<ref>[http://kywordsmith.com/#/paul-forms-exploratary-cmte/4533578818 "Rand Paul To Form Exploratory Committee For U.S. Senate Bid..."], www.kywordsmith.com. May 14, 2009</ref>

On July 28, 2009, Bunning announced that he would not run for re-election, after facing insufficient fundraising. This announcement left only Paul and [[Kentucky Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Trey Grayson]] as the remaining candidates for the Republican nomination,<ref>{{cite web|last=Memoli |first=Mike |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/politics_nation/2009/06/ky_sen_potential_bunning_chall.html |title=Politics Nation <U+2013> KY Sen: Potential Bunning Challenger Passes On Race |publisher=RealClearPolitics |date=June 15, 2009 |accessdate=May 19, 2010}}</ref> with Paul announcing on August 5, 2009 that he would officially run for the U.S. Senate as a Republican. The announcement was made through a series of national TV events, radio, and other programs, as well as through newspapers in Kentucky.<ref name=Gerth>{{cite web |last=Gerth |first=Joseph |date=August 5, 2009 |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20090805/NEWS0106/908050401/Paul+says+he+will+run+for+Senate |title=Paul says he will run for Senate |work=Courier-Journal |accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Giroux |first=Greg |date=August 5, 2009 |url=http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2009/08/rand-paul-declares-candidacy-f.html |title=Rand Paul Declares Candidacy For Kentucky Senate Seat |work=[[CQ Politics]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Keck |first=Kristi |date=August 6, 2009 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/08/06/kentucky.senate.paul/ |title=Ron Paul's son following in father's footsteps |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref>

====Early fundraising success====
On August 20, 2009, Paul's grassroots planned a [[moneybomb]] to kick off his campaign for United States Senate. The official campaign took in $433,509 in 24 hours. His website reported that this set a new record in Kentucky's political fundraising history in a 24-hour period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.randpaul2010.com/2009/08/rand-bomb-breaks-record/ |title=Rand Bomb Breaks Record |publisher=Randpaul2010.com |date=August 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref>

A second "moneybomb" was held on September 23, 2009, to counter a D.C. fundraiser being held for primary opponent Trey Grayson, by 23 Republican United States Senators, 17 of whom voted for the bank bailout.<ref>[http://bluegrasspolitics.bloginky.com/2009/08/31/web-site-promotes-fight-to-raise-money-for-paul/ "Lexington Herald-Leader <U+2013> Web site promotes 'fight' to raise money for Paul"], Bluegrass Politics September 1, 2009</ref> The theme was a [[UFC]] "fight" between Paul and "We the People" vs. Trey Grayson and the "D.C. Insiders."<ref>[http://www.kentuckyfight.com/ "Kentucky Fight <U+2013> Rand vs. Trey"], kentuckyfight.com September 1, 2009</ref> The money bomb ended up raising $186,276 for Paul in 24 hours on September 23;<ref>[http://i38.tinypic.com/1zfswzl.png "Rand Paul Graphs <U+2013> September 23, 2009"], tinypic.com September 24, 2009</ref> bringing Paul's Senate campaign's total raised to over one million. Later in the campaign, Paul claimed his pledge to not take money from lobbyists and Senators who had voted for the bailout was only a "primary pledge";<ref>{{cite news|last=Schreiner|first=Bruce|title=Rand Paul flips, seeks money from bailout senators|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/feedarticle/9139316|newspaper=The Guardian|date=June 23, 2010|location=London}}</ref> he subsequently held a DC fundraiser with the same Senators who had been the target of the September 23, 2009 "moneybomb."  Paul ended up raising some $3 million during the primary period.

====Primary victory====
[[File:Rand Paul & Jim Bunning by Gage Skidmore.jpg|left|thumb|Then-U.S. Senate candidate Rand Paul with then-Senator [[Jim Bunning]] at a rally in Hebron, Kentucky in November 2010.]]
Although Grayson was considered the frontrunner in July 2009,<ref>Jack Brammer [http://bluegrasspolitics.bloginky.com/2009/07/28/some-conservatives-skeptical-of-grayson/ Some conservatives wary of Grayson] ''[[Lexington Herald Leader]] July 28, 2009</ref> Paul found success characterizing Grayson as a "career politician" and challenging Grayson's conservatism. Paul ran an ad in February that made an issue out of Grayson's September 2008 admission that he voted for Bill Clinton when he was 20 years old.<ref>Jack Brammer [http://www.kentucky.com/2010/02/27/1158455/paul-attempts-to-tie-grayson-to.html Senate ads trade barbs on defense] ''[[Lexington Herald Leader]] February 27. 2010</ref> [[James Dobson]], a Christian evangelical figure, endorsed Grayson on April 26 based on the advice of what Dobson described as "senior members of the GOP", but on May 3 the Paul campaign announced that Dobson had changed his endorsement to Paul<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/05/dr-james-dobson-endorses-rand-paul/ Dr. James Dobson Endorses Rand Paul]  ''RandPaul2010.com''</ref> after Paul and some Paul supporters had lobbied Dobson insisting on Paul's social conservative bona fides.<ref>David Weigel [http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/05/james_dobson_endorses_rand_pau.html James Dobson endorses Rand Paul, apologizes for having previously backed his opponent] ''[[Washington Post]]'' May 3, 2010</ref>

On May 18 Paul won the Republican Senatorial primary by a 23.4% margin,<ref name="2010-primary">{{cite web|title=2010 Election map: Kentucky Senate |url=http://www.politico.com/2010/maps/#/Senate/2010/KY |publisher=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]] |date=May 18, 2010 |accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> meaning he would face the [[Attorney General of Kentucky|Kentucky Attorney General]] [[Jack Conway (politician)|Jack Conway]], in the November 2 general election.<ref name="demprimary">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wfpl.org/2010/05/19/conway-wins-democratic-primary-for-u-s-senate-seat/|title=Conway Wins Democratic Primary for U.S. Senate Seat|last=Gourlay|first=Kristin Espeland|date=May 18, 2010|work=WFPL radio|accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref>

===General campaign===
Main Article: ''[[United States Senate election in Kentucky, 2010]]''

In the 2010 general election, Paul faced [[Kentucky Attorney General]] [[Jack Conway]]. The campaign attracted $8.5 million dollars in contributions from outside groups, of which $6 million was spent to help Rand Paul and $2.5 million to help Conway. This money influx was in addition to the money spent by the candidates themselves: $6 million by Paul and $4.7 million by Conway. <ref>{{cite news|last=Steitzer|first=Stephanie|title=Outside groups spend big in U.S. Senate race|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20101029/NEWS0106/310290083?nclick_check=1|newspaper=Courier-Journal|date=Oct 29, 2010}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Super PACs|url=http://reporting.sunlightfoundation.com/outside-spending/race/KY-Senate|publisher=Sunlight Foundation}}</ref> 

On June 28, 2010, Rand Paul supporters held their first post-primary online fundraising drive, this time promoted as a "money blast."<ref>[http://www.gorandgo.com/ "GoRandGo.com <U+2013> Road to Victory Money Blast"], gorandgo.com/ June 7, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.whas11.com/news/local/Rand-Paul-supporters-plan-Moneyblast-95745464.html "Rand Paul supporters plan 'Moneyblast'"], June 7, 2010</ref> His campaign got off to a rough start after his comments on [[Civil Rights Act of 1964#Title II|Title II]] of Civil Rights Act of 1964 stirred controversy.<ref name="Thompson">Thompson, Krissah and Dan Balz. [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/20/AR2010052003500.html "Rand Paul comments about civil rights stir controversy"], ''The Washington Post'', May 21, 2010</ref> Paul stated that he favored 9 out of 10 titles of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]], but had he been a senator during 1960s, he would have raised some questions on the constitutionality of Title II of the Act.<ref>{{cite web|work=All Things Considered |url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126985068 |title=Rand Paul Says He Has A Tea Party 'Mandate' |publisher=NPR |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=September 10, 2010}}</ref> Paul said he abhors racism, and he would have marched with [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] to repeal [[Jim Crow Laws]]. he later released a statement declaring that he would have voted for the Act and stated "unequivocally ... that I will not support any efforts to repeal the Civil Rights Act of 1964".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whas11.com/community/blogs/political-blog/Rand-Paul-sits-down-with-Joe-Arnold-to-address-recent-controversial-statements-94665159.html |title=More raw video: Rand Paul sits down with Joe Arnold to address recent controversial statements |publisher=Whas11.com |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/05/rand-paul-sets-the-record-straight/ |title=Rand Paul Sets the Record Straight |publisher=Randpaul2010.com |date=May 20, 2010 |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> Later he generated more controversy by characterizing statements made by Obama administration officials regarding the [[BP oil spill]] cleanup as sounding "un-American".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/05/21/rand-paul-obama-sounds-un_n_584661.html |title=Rand Paul calls Obama's criticism of BP 'un-American' |publisher=News.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> 

One debate was held between the two candidates, at the [[University of Louisville]]. It was considered a very heated debate, in which both candidates made rude comments, centered around an ad run by Conway stating, "Why was Rand Paul a member of a secret society that called the Holy Bible 'a hoax,' that was banned for mocking Christianity and Christ?" Speaking about the ad, Paul stated, "We have serious problems in our country ... and he has descended into the gutter to attack my personal religious beliefs. ... Jack, you should be ashamed of yourself. You should apologize. Have you no decency? Have you no shame?" <ref>{{cite news|title=Senate debate in Kentucky devolves into a name-calling session|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/10/17/kentucky.senate.debate/index.html?_s=PM:POLITICS|newspaper=CNN|date=October 17, 2010}}</ref> Beyond the ad, Civil Rights, drugs and social security also were mentioned during the course of the heated debate. <ref>{{cite news|title=Obama, Civil Rights Centerpiece of Kentucky Senate Debate|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/10/11/obama-civil-rights-centerpiece-kentucky-senate-debate/#ixzz2P4OXKH24|newspaper=FOX News|date=October 11, 2010}}</ref> 

====Endorsements====
Paul has secured endorsements from several public figures and political organizations. They include the [[Downsize DC Foundation]],<ref>"[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ruc667e8qtA Rand Paul & DownsizeDC.org]", December 7, 2009.</ref> [[Concerned Women for America]],<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2009/12/women-4-rand/ "Women 4 Rand"], December 22, 2009</ref> [[Gun Owners of America]],<ref>"[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/01/gun-owners-of-america-endorse/ Gun Owners of America endorse]", January 6, 2010</ref> [[Steve Forbes]],<ref>"[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/01/steve-forbes-endorses/ Steve Forbes endorses]", January 7, 2010.</ref> [[FreedomWorks]],<ref>"[http://politics.theatlantic.com/2010/01/a_tea-party_target_list_freedomworks_releases_its_races_for_2010.php A Tea-Party Target List? FreedomWorks Releases Its Races For 2010]", January 25, 2010.</ref> [[Club for Growth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/endorsedcandidates/?subsec=0&id=752 |title=Club for Growth PAC Endorsed Candidates: Rand Paul (KY-Sen) |publisher=Clubforgrowth.org |date=July 30, 2010 |accessdate=October 8, 2010}}</ref> [[James Dobson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/home/permalink/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20100503005889&newsLang=en |title=Dr. James Dobson Endorses Rand Paul for Senate |publisher=Business Wire |date=May 3, 2010 |accessdate=September 10, 2010}}</ref> [[Sarah Palin]],<ref>"[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/02/sarah-palin-endorses/ Sarah Palin endorses]", February 1, 2010.</ref> [[Jim DeMint]],<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/05/jim_demint_endorses_rand_paul.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Jim DeMint endorses Rand Paul}}</ref> Cathy Bailey,<ref>Arnold, Joe. [http://www.whas11.com/community/blogs/political-blog/Cathy-Bailey-backing-Rand-Paul-in-primary-93430364.html Cathy Bailey backing Rand Paul in primary.] ''WHAS11.com'' May 11, 2010.</ref> [[Jim Bunning]],<ref>"[http://bluegrasspolitics.bloginky.com/2010/04/14/bunning-endorses-paul-in-us-senate-race/ Bunning endorses Paul in U.S. Senate race]", April 14, 2010.</ref> [[Erick Erickson]],<ref>[http://twitter.com/ewerickson/status/6673408098 "Erick Erickson on Twitter"], December 14, 2009</ref> [[National Federation of Independent Business]],<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/09/national-federation-of-independent-business-endorses-dr-rand-paul/ "National Federation of Independent Business Endorses Dr. Rand Paul"], 2010-9-23</ref> [[Citizens Against Government Waste|Council for Citizens Against Government Waste]],<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/09/council-for-citizens-against-government-waste-endorses-dr-rand-paul/ "Council For Citizens Against Government Waste Endorses Dr. Rand Paul"], 2010-9-23</ref> [[National Right to Life]],<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/09/national-right-to-life-endorses-rand-paul/ "National Right to Life Endorses Rand Paul"], 2010-9-17</ref> [[US Chamber of Commerce]],<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/09/us-chamber-of-commerce-endorses-rand-paul/ "US Chamber of Commerce Endorses Rand Paul"], 2010-9-15</ref> National Vietnam and Gulf War Veterans Coalition,<ref>[http://www.randpaul2010.com/2010/09/rand-paul-receives-endorsement-of-the-national-vietnam-and-gulf-war-veterans-coalition/ "Rand Paul Receives Endorsement of the National Vietnam and Gulf War Veterans Coalition"], 2010-9-09</ref> [[Mike Huckabee]],<ref>[http://www.huckpac.com/index.cfm?Fuseaction=Blogs.View&Blog_id=3217 "GOVERNOR MIKE HUCKABEE AND HUCK PAC ENDORSE RAND PAUL FOR U.S. SENATE IN KENTUCKY"], 2010-9-16</ref> and [[Tony Perkins (politician)|Tony Perkins]]/[[FRC Action PAC]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Trish Turner|title=Religious Attack Ad Rallies Conservatives to Rand Paul's Side|newspaper=FoxNews.com|date=October 21, 2010|url=http://politics.blogs.foxnews.com/2010/10/21/religious-attack-ad-rallies-conservatives-rand-pauls-side|accessdate=October 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|publisher=FRC Action PAC|date=October 22, 2010|title=FRC Action PAC Endorses Rand Paul for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.frcaction.org/frcapacinternal/frc-action-pac-endorses-rand-paul-for-us-senate|accessdate=October 24, 2010}}</ref>

==U.S. Senate career==

===Tenure===
[[File:Rand Paul ceremonial swearing in.jpg|right|thumb|Senator Rand Paul being sworn-in by Vice President [[Joe Biden]], along with his family, in the [[Old Senate Chamber]] in the [[United States Capitol]] building.]]
Paul was sworn in on January 5, 2011&nbsp;along with his father, marking the first time in congressional history that someone served in the Senate while their parent simultaneously served in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|last=Douglas|first=William|title=Father watches with pride as Rand Paul becomes U.S. senator|publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]| date=January 5, 2011|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2011/01/05/106256/father-watches-with-pride-as-rand.html#storylink=misearch|accessdate=January 29, 2011}}</ref> He was assigned to serve on the [[United States Senate Committee on Energy and Natural Resources|Energy and Natural Resources]], [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Health, Education, Labor and Pensions]], [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Homeland Security and Government Affairs]], and [[United States Senate Committee on Small Business and Entrepreneurship|Small Business]] committees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Four committee assignments for Rand Paul|work=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=January 28, 2011|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2011/01/28/1614138/four-committee-assignments-for.html|accessdate=January 29, 2011}}</ref> Paul also formed the [[Tea Party Caucus#Members of Senate Caucus|Senate Tea Party Caucus]] with [[Jim DeMint]] and [[Mike Lee (U.S. politician)|Mike Lee]] as its inaugural members.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sonmez|first=Felicia|title=Rand Paul announces Senate Tea Party Caucus|work=The Washington Post|date=January 14, 2011|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2011/01/rand-paul-announces-senate-tea.html|accessdate=January 29, 2011}}</ref> His first legislative proposal was to cut $500&nbsp;billion from federal spending in one year. This proposal includes cutting the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] by 83&nbsp;percent and the [[Department of Homeland Security]] by 43&nbsp;percent, as well as folding the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] into the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] and eliminating the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]]. Seven independent agencies would be eliminated and food stamps would be cut by 30&nbsp;percent. Under Paul's proposal, defense spending would be reduced by 6.5&nbsp;percent and [[international aid]] would be eliminated.<ref>{{cite news|last=Straub|first=Bill|title=Kentucky Sen. Rand Paul rolls out budget ax|work=[[Evansville Courier & Press]]|date=January 28, 2011|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/2011/jan/27/sen-paul-rolls-out-budget-ax/|accessdate=January 29, 2011 }}
* {{cite news|last =Carroll|first =James R.|date=January 25, 2011|title=Senator Rand Paul seeks $500 billion in federal spending cuts|work=The Courier-Journal| url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/2248953991.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+25%2C+2011&author=James+R+Carroll&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=n%2Fa&desc=Senator+Rand+Paul+seeks+%24500+billion+in+federal+spending+cuts|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}
* {{cite news|last=Freddoso|first=David|date=January 26, 2011|title=A detailed look at the Rand Paul spending bill|work=[[The Washington Examiner]]| url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/blogs/beltway-confidential/2011/01/detailed-look-rand-paul-spending-bill|accessdate=April 9, 2011}}</ref> He later proposed a five-year budget plan intended to balance the budget.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bruce|first=Mary|title=Sen. Paul Unveils 5-Year Budget Plan: Eliminates Four Federal Agencies|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=March 17, 2011|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2011/03/sen-paul-unveils-5-year-budget-plan-eliminates-four-federal-agencies.html|accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref>

In February, Paul was one of two Republicans to vote against extending three key provisions of the [[USA PATRIOT Act]] ([[roving wiretap]]s, searches of business records, and conducting surveillance of "lone wolves" <U+2014> individuals not linked to terrorist groups).<ref>{{cite news|last=Sonmez|first=Felicia|title=Senate passes short-term extension of Patriot Act provisions|work=The Washington Post|date =February 15, 2011|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2011/02/senate-to-vote-tuesday-on-shor.html|accessdate =February 17, 2011}}</ref> In May, he remained the last senator opposing the PATRIOT Act, and was ultimately defeated on May 26.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/05/26/patriot-act-extension-passes-senate_n_867736.html|accessdate=May 26, 2011|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=May 26, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5yz8uVD4V|archivedate=May 26, 2011|first=Alexander|last=Belenky|title=Patriot Act Extension Passes Senate, Rand Paul Amendments Fail}}</ref>

On March 2, Paul was one of nine senators to vote against a stopgap bill that cut $4&nbsp;billion from the budget and temporarily prevent a [[government shutdown]], citing that it did not cut enough from the budget.<ref>{{cite news|last=Middleton|first=Neil|title=Yarmuth and Paul vote no on stopgap spending bill|publisher=[[WYMT-TV]]|date=March 2, 2011|url=http://www.wkyt.com/blogs/neilsnotebook/Yarmuth_and_Paul_vote_no_on_stopgap_GOP_spending_bill_117271378.html|accessdate=March 4, 2011}}</ref> One week later, he voted against the Democratic and Republican budget proposals to keep funding the federal government, citing that both bills did not cut enough spending. Both bills failed to pass the senate.<ref>{{cite news| last =Ferrechio| first =Susan| title =Senate rejects budget plans 9 days before deadline| work=The Washington Examiner| date =March 9, 2011| url =http://washingtonexaminer.com/politics/congress/2011/03/senate-rejects-budget-plans-9-days-deadline| accessdate =March 10, 2011 }}</ref> He later voted against stopgap measures on March 17 and April 8, both of which passed the senate.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jaffe|first=Matthew|title=Kickin' the Can: Senate Passes Stop-Gap Spending Plan, Buys Lawmakers Three More Weeks To Solve Funding Mess|publisher=ABC News|date =March 17, 2011|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2011/03/kickin-the-can-senate-passes-stop-gap-spending-plan-buys-lawmakers-three-more-weeks-to-solve-funding.html|accessdate=April 9, 2011}}
*{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Scott|title=Rand Paul opposes temporary stopgap |work=Politico|date =April 9, 2011|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/glennthrush/0411/Rand_Paul_opposes_temporary_stopgap_.html|accessdate=April 9, 2011}}</ref> On April 14, He was one of 19 senators to vote against a budget that cut $38.5&nbsp;billion from the budget and fund the government for the remainder of the fiscal year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bowman|first=Quinn|title=House, Senate Pass Bipartisan Budget Deal to Fund Government |publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service]]|date =April 14, 2011|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/2011/04/house-passes-385-budget-deal-to-fund-government.html|accessdate=May 26, 2011}}</ref> Paul voiced opposition to U.S. intervention in the [[2011 Libyan civil war|Libyan civil war]] and has criticized President Obama for not gaining congressional consent for [[Operation Odyssey Dawn]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Straub|first=Bill|title=Kentucky Senator Paul berates Obama for 'cavalierly taking us to war{{'-}}|work=Evansville Courier & Press|date=March 30, 2011|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/2011/mar/30/kentucky-senator-paul-berates-obama-cavalierly-tak/|accessdate=April 14, 2011 }}
* {{cite news|last =Sonmez|first =Felicia|date=March 17, 2011|title=Rand Paul opposes U.S. military involvement in Libya|work=The Washington Post| url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/post/rand-paul-opposes-us-military-involvement-in-libya/2011/03/17/ABkw6jl_blog.html|accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> During the [[United States debt-ceiling crisis of 2011|debt ceiling crisis]], the Senator stated that he would only support raising the debt ceiling if a [[balanced budget amendment]] was enacted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Klein|first=Rick|title=Sen. Rand Paul: No Debt Ceiling Increase Without Balanced Budget Amendment|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2011/06/sen-rand-paul-no-debt-ceiling-increase-without-balanced-budget-amendment.html|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=August 3, 2011|date=June 30, 2011}}</ref> Paul was a supporter of the [[Cut, Cap and Balance Act]], which was [[Table (parliamentary procedure)|tabled]] by the Democrats.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hayward|first=John|title=Cut, Cap, and Balance Killed|url=http://www.humanevents.com/article.php?id=45039|work=[[Human Events]]|accessdate=August 3, 2011|date=July 22, 2011}}</ref> On August 3, Paul voted against a bill that would raise the debt ceiling.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marchmon|first=Jay|title=Rand Paul reacts to passage of debt ceiling bill|url=http://www.wpsdlocal6.com/news/local/Rand-Paul-reacts-to-passage-of-debt-ceiling-bill-126594128.html|publisher=[[WPSD-TV]]|accessdate=August 3, 2011|date=August 2, 2011}}</ref>

On September 7, Paul called for a vote of no confidence in Treasury Secretary Timothy Geithner.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Siobhan|title=Rand Paul Calls for No Confidence on Geithner|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2011/09/07/rand-paul-calls-for-no-confidence-vote-on-geithner/|accessdate=September 8, 2011|work=Wall Street Journal|date=September 8, 2011}}</ref> Later that month, Paul blocked legislation that would strengthen safety rules for oil and gas pipelines because he felt the bill was not strong enough.<ref>{{cite news|last=Simon|first=Richard|title=Rand Paul blocks pipeline-safety bill, frustrating Californians|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/nationnow/2011/10/fight-erupts-in-congress-over-pipeline-safety-legislation-.html|accessdate=October 28, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 5, 2011}}</ref> In October, Paul blocked a bill that would provide $36&nbsp;million in benefits for elderly and disabled refugees, saying that he was concerned that it could be used to aid domestic terrorists. This was in response to two alleged terrorists, who came to the United States through a refugee program and were receiving welfare benefits, were arrested in 2011&nbsp;in Paul<U+2019>s hometown of Bowling Green.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Scott|title=Rand Paul blocking refugee funds|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65142.html|accessdate=October 4, 2011|work=Politico|date=October 5, 2011}}</ref> Paul lifted his hold on the bill after Democratic leaders promised to hold a congressional hearing into how individuals are selected for refugee status and request an investigation on how the two suspects were admitted in the country through a refugee program.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Scott|title=Rand Paul ends hold on SSI benefits|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65142.html|accessdate=October 28, 2011|work=Politico|date=October 17, 2011}}</ref>
 
For the 113th Congress, Paul was added to the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Foreign Relations committee]] and retained his spot on the Health, Education, Labor and Pensions, Homeland Security and Government Affairs, and Small Business committees.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=Daniel|title=Rand Paul on the Foreign Relations Committee <U+2014> and What It Means|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/rand-paul-on-foreign-relations-committee/|publisher=''The American Conservative''|accessdate=March 29, 2013|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref> 

===Filibuster history===

On March 6<U+2013>7, 2013, Paul engaged in a talking [[Filibuster in the United States Senate|filibuster]] to block voting on the nomination of [[John O. Brennan]] as the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|Director of the CIA]], questioning [[Barack Obama]] and [[Obama administration|his administration's]] use of [[unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]], and the stated legal justification for hypothetical lethal use within the United States. [[File:Rand Paul Filibuster.png|right|thumb|Rand Paul speaking during his filibuster.]]Paul held the floor for 12 hours and 52 minutes<ref>{{cite news|title=Rand Paul Ends Epic Mr. Smith-Style Filibuster After More Than 12 Hours|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2013/03/06/rand_paul_is_waging_an_epic_mr_smith_style_filibuster_right_now.html|author=Josh Voorhees|work=Slate|date=March 7, 2013}}</ref>, at times ceding to several other Republican senators as well as one Democratic senator, [[Ron Wyden]], who joined in questioning the use of drones and related topics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sen. Paul holds floor for hours in filibuster of CIA nominee, over drone concerns|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2013/03/06/sen-paul-holds-floor-for-hours-in-filibuster-cia-nominee-over-drone-concerns/|publisher=Fox News|date=March 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>http://www.politico.com/story/2013/03/rand-paul-filibuster-john-brennan-cia-nominee-88507.html</ref> He noted the purpose of the filibuster was mostly regarding drone policy, particularly usage on noncombatants on U.S. soil. He argued that the language administration officials had used when questioned over that potential usage of drones was unclear, and could potentially lead to a slippery slope where citizens could be targeted merely for expressing views different than those of the president. He asked for the [[Obama administration|administration]] to say they will not target noncombatants on U.S. soil.<ref>http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/03/07/rand-paul-brennan-filibuster/1969869/</ref> Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] replied later on March 7, stating that the president does not have the authority to use weaponized drones within the U.S. [[Extrajudicial punishment|to kill]], without [[Due Process Clause|due process]], Americans not engaged in combat; he stated that he was "quite happy" with the response.<ref>http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2013/03/07/obama-administration-responds-to-paul-on-drones/</ref> During the filibuster, Paul was able to appeal to many other voters, including some who had not previously supported him or his father, [[Ron Paul]]. He was also able to appeal to voters who had supported his father, but were skeptical towards him.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2013/03/07/politics/rand-paul-ron-paul/index.html Rand Paul scores points with father's skeptical supporters]</ref> Paul said he was amazed by the support he got from Americans and from fellow senators and even congressman who entered the senate chamber against custom, in order to show their support. Even [[Nevada]] Senator and [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Harry Reid]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Merica|first=Dan|title=Rand Paul scores points with father's skeptical supporters|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/03/07/politics/rand-paul-ron-paul/?hpt=hp_t1|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Madison|first=Lucy|title=Rand Paul 'amazed' by support for filibuster|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-250_162-57573056/rand-paul-amazed-by-support-for-filibuster/|publisher=CBS News|date=March 7, 2013}}</ref> and satirical talk show host [[Jon Stewart]] expressed some praise for Paul.<ref>{{cite news|last=Poor|first=Jeff|title=Jon Stewart voices support for Rand Paul filibuster: 'Holy Howard Roark's ghost{{'-}}|url=http://dailycaller.com/2013/03/07/jon-stewart-voices-support-for-rand-paul-filibuster-holy-howard-roarks-ghost-video/#ixzz2MuDXVbf7|newspaper=Daily Caller|date=March 7, 2013}}</ref>

On March 25, 2013, an announcement was made by senators Ted Cruz, Rand Paul, and [[Mike Lee (U.S. politician)|Mike Lee]], threatening that they would hold more filibusters over any pieces of legislation that enforce [[Gun control#Gun control in the United States|gun control]] on the house floor, in the Senate. The [[White House Office|White House]] prompted a warning letter, in response. <ref>{{cite news|last]Allen|first=Jonathan|title=Rand Paul and Ted Cruz threaten filibuster on guns|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/03/rand-paul-and-ted-cruz-threaten-filibuster-on-guns-89299.html}}</ref>

