===Speculation on future===
[[File:Rand Paul by Gage Skidmore 7.jpg|right|thumb|Rand Paul speaking at the 2013 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in National Harbor, Maryland on March 14, 2013.]]
After the 2012 Election, Rand was often in the news speaking on how the Republican Party needs to adapt to the country's changing demographics and beliefs. In a radio interview with [[Aaron Klein]], Paul spoke about a possible 2016 presidency bid. He said he was not promising a run but did say he would make a decision within the next two years. He also mentioned that even if he does not run, he is still planning on re-shaping the way GOP handles certain policies.<ref>http://www.politico.com/story/2013/01/rand-paul-gop-must-evolve-and-adapt-86473.html</ref>

On February 13, 2013, Rand Paul delivered the official "Tea Party" response to President Obama's state of the union speech.  <ref>http://www.politico.com/story/2013/02/tea-party-rebuttal-text-of-rand-paul-response-87557.html</ref>  [[Marco Rubio]] gave the official GOP response which prompted some pundits to call February 13, 2013 the start of the 2016 GOP primaries.<ref>http://www.npr.org/2013/02/14/172034468/rand-paul-big-governments-not-a-friend-to-those-who-are-trying-to-get-ahead</ref>

On March 14, Paul gave a speech at the 2013 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in Washington DC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/03/2016-rubio-paul-et-al-court-cpac-crowd-88884.html|title=CPAC 2013: Marco Rubio, Rand Paul fight for the future of the GOP|author=Lois Romano|publisher=Politico|date=March 14, 2013|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> He also won the 2013 CPAC straw poll on March 16, winning 25% of the votes cast.<ref>http://firstread.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/03/16/17341131-rand-paul-wins-cpac-straw-poll-rubio-close-second?lite</ref>

==Political positions==

Paul supports [[term limit]]s, a [[Balanced Budget Amendment#United States|balanced budget amendment]], and the [[Read the Bills Act]], in addition to the widespread reduction of federal spending and taxation. He has gained prominence for his independent positions on many political issues, often clashing with both [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].<ref name="schreiner1"/> He received a perfect score from the [[Gun Owners of America]], [[National Right to Life Committee]], and the [[American Conservative Union]]. [[National Journal]] gave him a 100% conservative record in 2011. <ref>{{cite web|title=Senator Rand Paul|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/117285/rand-paul#.UViCpRybP5I|work=Project VoteSmart|publisher=Votesmart.org|accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref> On [[Fox News]], Senator Paul was quoted as saying Congress' political position is "10 years behind the American Public." 
<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Eliana|title=Paul: Congress <U+2018>Ten Years Behind the American Public<U+2019>|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/343776/paul-congress-ten-years-behind-american-public-eliana-johnson|newspaper=National Review|date=March 24, 2013}}</ref> 

[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]] noted that Rand Paul had the "Art of a political salesman," and was able to market his ideas to his audience, adding that his ability to disagree with his party often helps him win in an argument. <ref>{{cite news|last=Altman|first=Alex|title=In Kentucky, Rand Paul Demonstrates the Art of the Sale|url=http://swampland.time.com/2013/03/29/in-kentucky-rand-paul-demonstrates-the-art-of-the-sale/#ixzz2P91ByTQa|accessdate=March 31st, 2013|newspaper=TIME Magazine|date=March 29th, 2013}}</ref> In the hours after his filibuster, CNN noted that Paul "Can shape the future of conservatism."
 
There has been some disagreement over whether or not Paul is a [[Libertarianism|libertarian]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} He has stated that he is "not quite" a libertarian, including in a [[USA Today]] column that he wrote. He considers himself to be a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] follower, who wants smaller government, but not quite a libertarian. <ref>{{cite news|last=Paul|first=Rand|title=Rand Paul, libertarian? Not quite.|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/opinion/forum/2010-08-10-column10_ST2_N.htm|newspaper=USA Today|date=August 9th, 2010}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title=Paul Ryan's & Rand Paul's Libertarianism|url=http://www.ohio.com/blogs/mass-destruction/blog-of-mass-destruction-1.298992/paul-ryan-s-rand-paul-s-libertarianism-1.384362|newspaper=Ohio Journal|date=March 26th, 2013}}</ref> In a March 2013 interview with [[Sean Hannity]], Paul said that he identifies as both a "[[Constitutionalism|constitutional]] [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]" and a "[[Libertarian conservatism|libertarian conservative]]."<ref>{{cite news|title=Sen. Paul Discusses CPAC Win|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O6w__gMkJ58|YouTube|date=March 27th, 2013}}</ref><!-- I am not completely sure of this wording, but I was trying to give the argument of whether or not he is a libertarian. I know there have been some disagreements in the past, but I feel it should be included. --> Unlike his more stridently "non-interventionist" father, Rand sees a role for American armed forces abroad, including permanent foreign military bases.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/01/rand-paul-military-bases_n_2981368.html "Rand Paul Supports Some Military Bases On Foreign Soil, A Big Difference From His Dad."]</ref>

==Personal life==
In [[Atlanta]], Paul met Kelley Ashby, a [[Rhodes College]] [[English studies|English]] major. Paul and Ashby were married on October 20, 1990, and moved to [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]], less than {{convert|30|mi|km}} from her hometown of [[Russellville, Kentucky]], in 1993.<ref name=ndl>{{Cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=KNDB&p_theme=kndb&p_text_direct-0=11CC367E848ECF20&p_field_direct-0=document_id |title=Local tie to Paul; RHS grad a daughter-in-law to Republican president hopeful |last=Cassady |first=Pam |work=News Democrat & Leader |year=2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2009}}</ref>

Kelley Paul is a freelance writer, and she manages payroll and marketing communications for Paul's surgical practice.<ref name=xmas/> The couple have three sons: William, Duncan and Robert.<ref name=mp/>

